{{unreferenced|date= December 2010}} 
A '''trade office''', sometimes known as a '''trade representation''', '''commercial office''', or '''trade mission''', is an official establishment that promotes the [[commerce|commercial]] interests of a [[government]] (such as a city, state, or country) in a foreign [[Capital city|capital]]. The head of such an establishment is typically called a [[trade representative]] or commercial representative.

==Taiwan==
{{main|Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office}}

Due to the [[Foreign relations of Taiwan|limited recognition]] of the Republic of China ([[Taiwan]]) as a result of the [[China|People's Republic of China]]'s [[One-China policy]], many countries do not have formal diplomatic relations with the Taiwanese government. Taiwan's interests in these countries and these countries' interests in Taiwan are usually represented by one or more trade missions which function as [[de facto embassy|de facto embassies]] or [[consulate]]s.

